lls with a cell counter (keep the range of correct measurement of the device into account). <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227636,"guid":"6E4530A5050D4E248A623E7D9CC5C89F","previous_id":1227635,"previous_guid":"C0C74AEA52D348FDB7CBCD2E9F8D11AC","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"F5841DEDE38945D9A8F6EF9BF2E40C59","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 0"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"0F753BBD4F9341CDB2413861DEE5B719","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Based on the cell count, dilute the cells to seed a suitable amount in a 96-well plate. <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">For example, you want to put 20.000 cells in 200 \u00b5L medium in each well of a 96-well. The cell counter says you have 500.000 cells\/mL. How do you proceed?<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\"><\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Figure out the dilution factor first. You start from 500.000 cells\/mL, which needs to be diluted to 20.000 cells\/200 \u00b5L.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">      ---> 20.000 cells\/200 \u00b5L = 100.000 cells\/1.000 \u00b5L = 100.000 cells\/mL<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">      ---> 500.000 cells\/mL \/\/ 100.000 cells\/mL = 5 (=dilution factor).<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">200 \u00b5L is needed for each well (96 wells in total). This means a total of 19,2 mL of cell suspension is required. Make 25 mL just to be sure there is enough.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Put in a 50 mL falcon, 20 mL medium and 5 mL 500.000 cells\/mL, and mix<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Put the cell suspension in a white tray and use a multichannel to put 200 \u00b5L into each well.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">      ---> 20.000 cells\/200 \u00b5L = 100.000 cells\/1.000 \u00b5L = 100.000 cells\/mL<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">      ---> 500.000 cells\/mL \/\/ 100.000 cells\/mL = 5 (=dilution factor).<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">200 \u00b5L is needed for each well (96 wells in total). This means a total of 19,2 mL of cell suspension is required. Make 25 mL just to be sure there is enough.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Put in a 50 mL falcon, 20 mL medium and 5 mL 500.000 cells\/mL, and mix<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Put the cell suspension in a white tray and use a multichannel to put 200 \u00b5L into each well.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227637,"guid":"A7F3A853E7A24A98B06CDA251F863E95","previous_id":1227636,"previous_guid":"6E4530A5050D4E248A623E7D9CC5C89F","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"B9F1B0E74F114D189E78A4A10D247494","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 0"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"62C582C493B04ABF9D89D3DCA66787A7","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Leave the cells <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> in the incubator on <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span> CO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2 <\/span><span>(temperature and\/or CO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2 <\/span><span>concentration may change depending on the cell type).<\/span><\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"742856A0F5F711EBAF7B034EEAA6AE29","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":0,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"6B0F63B0F5F711EBAF7B034EEAA6AE29","order_id":3,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":37,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"6E5FEE40F5F711EBAF7B034EEAA6AE29","order_id":4,"type_id":25,"title":"concentration","source":{"concentration":5,"unit":null,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227638,"guid":"C12C80E8FB4F465183AF5786D2FAFBAB","previous_id":1227637,"previous_guid":"A7F3A853E7A24A98B06CDA251F863E95","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"365A47E72FBA49A690EF2B33BC96112D","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 1"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"EE42DF91892142D4926CC71BA8462801","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">LENTIVIRAL TRANSDUCTION<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227639,"guid":"C6F45F33C46D4291907D457EB4320729","previous_id":1227638,"previous_guid":"C12C80E8FB4F465183AF5786D2FAFBAB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"F093957EF2B44A9E9D8C557E5684BC29","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 1"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"B8378E58861A4E25A527F1769FB4385C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Thaw the vector you want to transduce your cells with<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227640,"guid":"644AAE8560704982A789BC76352EB9EA","previous_id":1227639,"previous_guid":"C6F45F33C46D4291907D457EB4320729","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"49D2F5D261DD45919BE13D2F67E6C632","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 1"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"253D7847B7D0406FAC9EBD5F5DA0A51C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Inspect the well plate macroscopically and microscopically. <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Did the color change of the medium? Is the color change the same in each well? Do the cells look healthy?<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227641,"guid":"27F0C288DFB042CDB6F1A4843899D795","previous_id":1227640,"previous_guid":"644AAE8560704982A789BC76352EB9EA","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"B6BB7D1E541F4C7C95BE5D487321EF55","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 1"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"BC2F9CAB1DFB4E008EFAFAA21C7BD1C1","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><ol style = \"list-style-type: decimal;\"><\/ol><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Fill the wells with 100 \u00b5L medium<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Add 50 \u00b5L vector to the first well and mix by pipetting up and down.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Start a serial dilution by taking 50 \u00b5L of the first well and adding it to the second well. Mix again by pipetting up and down.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span>Incubate 2-3 days in the incubator 37 \u00b0C at 5% CO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\"><\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"blob:https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/71a315cc-6b40-4c67-aff5-ae24dc921443\" \/><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><\/ul><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227642,"guid":"53956FCEDD5746EEBCFA528B37FDBFD2","previous_id":1227641,"previous_guid":"27F0C288DFB042CDB6F1A4843899D795","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"14D00AB3C68F488F8F3D52FCF4B922BE","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 3\/4"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"985B76A4604741A6A69C630AF71FB908","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">SELECTION OF CELLS<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227643,"guid":"51572913910A47B7B061A548E72114FE","previous_id":1227642,"previous_guid":"53956FCEDD5746EEBCFA528B37FDBFD2","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"A4AD8B7FBB664D54856AFFA70E7C113F","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Day 3\/4"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"AAF233CFE82545309D88326214391E03","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Usually, a vector with a selection gene (puromycin, hygromycin, blasticidin, ....) is used to transduce the cells. To check how well the cells were transduced, in other words,. how good the vector works. Cells are transferred to a 24-well plate and are given medium with selection. Only transduced cells will survive. Depending on how good the vector works, cells transduced with more diluted vector will also survive. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">More concentrated vector could also be toxic to cells. Check each well for which vector dilution is the best. Depending on the purpose of the experiments you want to conduct, you keep cells transduced with a higher\/lower vector dilution. <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span>always take along 2 wells of non-transduced cells during the selection process. Put one well on selection and the other on regular medium. All the non-transduced cells should die off (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">if this is not the case, increase the concentration of the selection<\/span><span>).<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Other methods of separating the transduced cells from non-transduced cells is via Fluorescence Activated Cell Sortingt (FACS). If the vector carries a reporter gene (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">for example eGFP, mCherry,...<\/span><span>) or a cluster of differentiation (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">for example tCD34, CD4, CD8,...<\/span><span>), they can be sorted via FACS.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1227644,"guid":"D28FB58FA2324E27AE650767D1EDFFFF","pre